In .NET MAUI, the theme API lives on `Application.Current`:

**Detect current theme**
```csharp
AppTheme current = Application.Current.RequestedTheme; // Dark, Light, or Unspecified
```

**React to system theme changes in real time**
```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to {e.RequestedTheme}");
    // Update UI or re-apply colors here
};
```

**Force a specific theme (overrides system setting)**
```csharp
// Lock to dark mode regardless of device setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Revert to following the system
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

**Practical pattern — wire it up in `App.xaml.cs`:**
```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme → {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // e.g. swap resource dictionaries, update bound properties, etc.
    }

    public void SetThemeOverride(AppTheme theme)
    {
        UserAppTheme = theme; // Dark, Light, or Unspecified (follow system)
    }
}
```

**In XAML**, you can also use `AppThemeBinding` to declaratively respond:
```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` — read-only, reflects the OS setting.
- `UserAppTheme` — read/write, your override. Set to `Unspecified` to follow the system again.
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires when the **system** theme changes (even if you've overridden with `UserAppTheme`).
- `AppThemeBinding` in XAML reacts to both system and user-forced theme changes automatically.
